  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 접해(鰈海) : '
    value: 우리나라 근해에 가자미가 많이 나므로, 우리나라를 접해라 한다.
english:
  title: Edict Conferring the Title of Chamberlain upon Pan Pok-hae
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    It is said that only through sudden crisis and urgent peril do we recognize true talent that stands above the multitude. Only through establishing brilliant and noble deeds do we receive rare and supreme favor. Thus since ancient times, sage emperors and wise kings, virtuous ministers and capable counselors have kept wealth and honor inseparable from their persons and transmitted their names through ten thousand generations.

    Behold you, Pok-hae. Your ancestor Fu received the mandate of envoy and opened relations with Japan, wielding the authority of letters to select gifted talents. Generation after generation, your house produced renowned worthies who graced the court. The teachings of poetry and books, the virtue of ritual and righteousness—all were cultivated and magnified, growing ever greater. In you, Pok-hae, does this legacy shine forth.

    You possess a spirit that harmonizes both strength and gentleness, talents that unite both letters and arms. Your resolve stands firm as metal and stone. You have transformed filial piety into loyalty, forgetting yourself in service to your sovereign. Thus it is fitting that you shouldered the burden when your lord faced sudden peril.

    In the Year of the Tiger, when I ventured west to hunt, a great wild boar rushed before me. Those at my side paled with fear, not knowing what to do. My life hung by a thread. Then you, Pok-hae, galloped forth on horseback, and with a single arrow pierced its belly. As the bowstring sang, the beast fell. Thus did you extend my life, as though stealing me back from Heaven itself.

    Though the spirits of our ancestor shrine and sacred mountains silently moved your heart, without the loyalty you harbor within and the courage you were born with, how could I, this unworthy ruler, continue to serve our nation and these sacred lands?

    Looking to precedent, I grant you the royal surname and adopt you as my son. I elevate you to the rank of Chamberlain—to distinguish my favor and to encourage such loyalty and valor. I appoint your father to serve as Minister of the Right—to promote such devotion to duty. The Han dynasty swore to its meritorious ministers: "Let Mount Tai wear smooth as a whetstone, let the Yellow River narrow to a ribbon, that our realm endure eternal and pass down to all descendants." Now I too make this pledge: "Let the flatfish seas grow dry as dust, let not a drop remain—yet your descendants, as my own blood, shall be the strong pillars of our nation."

    Hark, Pok-hae! Heed this command with reverence. Strive without ceasing, honor without wavering.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'flatfish seas' refers to the waters near Korea, rich in flounder, and thus becomes a poetic name for the Korean peninsula itself.
